> Fruit salsas are one of our favorite ways to jazz up recipes in a way that's both kid- and adult-friendly. The little ones will love the sweetness in the pineapple here, while moms and dads will appreciate how it creates a flavor mash-up with the gently spiced pieces of fish. And everyone will agree that it's fun, satisfying, and refreshing when packed into a tortilla.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat broiler to high. Drain @pineapple{12%ounce}, then place in a #medium bowl{}. Chop half the @cilantro{1/2%ounce}(chopped) (save the rest for garnish). Halve one @lime{1}; cut other @lime{1} into wedges. Halve and peel @shallot{1}(minced until you have 1 TBSP). Mince @garlic{1/2%teaspoon} until you have ½ tsp (you will have some left over).

Add shallot, half the chopped cilantro, and a squeeze of lime to bowl with pineapple. Toss to combine. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Place @tilapia{22%ounce} on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Sprinkle with a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon}. Season all over with salt, pepper, and @southwest spice blend{2%tablespoon}. Rub seasonings into tilapia to moisten. Place under broiler and broil until opaque and lightly charred, about ~{8%minutes}.

Meanwhile, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, @mayonnaise{4%tablespoon}, @water{1%tablespoon}, a squeeze of lime, and a pinch of garlic in a small bowl. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Add more or less garlic to taste, or leave it out entirely depending on how you like it.

In another medium bowl, toss @shredded red cabbage{8%ounce}, remaining chopped cilantro, @sugar{1%teaspoon}, a squeeze of lime, and 2 TBSP crema. Season with salt, pepper, and more lime (to taste).

Wrap @flour tortillas{12} in a damp #paper towel{} and microwave on high until warm, about ~{30%seconds}. Break up tilapia into bite-sized pieces. Fill each tortilla with tilapia, slaw, and salsa. Drizzle with crema. Tear leaves from reserved cilantro and scatter over top. Serve with lime wedges for squeezing over.